ABSOLUTE BLOCK SET TO END ON THE EAST COASTWAY

Network Rail is in the process of introducing colour light signalling on the Seaford branch in East Sussex and abolishing three mechanical signal boxes. The branch is to be controlled from Three Bridges Rail Operating Centre (ROC).

The project includes work to five level crossings; installation of three new relocatable equipment buildings (REBs) at Lewes, Newhaven Marine and Cooksbridge; replacement signal structures; and the installation of a new turnback move at Lewes. Principal contractor on the job is Atkins, with design by SNC-Lavalin and the project executed in an alliance with Network Rail. According to Richard Sayell, Network Rail’s project manager, the objectives of the project are:

■ changes between Lewes and Southerham Junction (where the Seaford branch diverges from the East Coastway) to improve Lewes as a diversionary route for the Brighton main line, upping the London to Brighton via Lewes capacity from one to three trains per hour;

■ install LED signal heads throughout (29 signals);

■ replace switch diamonds at Southerham Junction with clamplocks to improve resilience;

■ renewal of Cooksbridge level crossing;

